    "answer": "## Task Framing\n\n**Task**: Update `README.md`'s \"Install (Windows)\" section. The current text is a placeholder \u2014 it says \"nix doesn't run on Windows, so dependencies are installed globally\" and tersely shows `.\\visual-relay launch`, omitting all the Windows-specific prerequisites, toolchain provisioning, sandbox setup, and caveats that actually exist in the codebase. The update must replace this with accurate, actionable Windows installation guidance.\n\n**Context discovered**:\n- The macOS install uses Nix to auto-provision every dependency. Windows has no Nix, so `visual-relay.ps1` handles equivalent provisioning natively: it checks for **Git** (hard requirement), **.NET 10 SDK** (auto-installs on consent via `dotnet-install.ps1` or `winget`), and **uv** (soft requirement for the LiteLLM model backend).\n- Running `.\\visual-relay launch` actually invokes `visual-relay.cmd` \u2192 `visual-relay.ps1`, which provisions the toolchain and then runs `dotnet run` on the C# CLI.\n- **Sandboxing** on Windows uses **MXC** (Microsoft Execution Containers) via `wxc-exec`. Users must run `visual-relay provision-mxc` post-clone, or opt into the degraded builtin sandbox.\n- **State locations** differ: `%APPDATA%\\visual-relay\\` for settings, `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\visual-relay\\` for caches/venv.\n- PowerShell execution policy can block the `.ps1` \u2014 the `.cmd` shim already passes `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass`, so users should prefer `.\\visual-relay launch`.\n- Git hooks work through Git for Windows' bundled bash.\n\n---\n\n## Solution Options\n\n**Option A \u2014 Comprehensive step-by-step (full rewrite)**\nReplace the Windows section with a detailed walkthrough covering: pre\u2011clone prerequisites (Git, .NET 10 SDK, uv) with install commands (winget / dotnet-install.ps1), the clone + launch flow explained step\u2011by\u2011step, MXC sandbox setup (`provision-mxc`), state location callout, execution\u2011policy tip, and a cross\u2011reference to TROUBLESHOOTING.md for deeper Windows troubleshooting. This gives Windows users a self\u2011contained guide without needing to chase links.\n\n**Option B \u2014 Concise \"what the launcher does\" (minimal diff)**\nKeep the section brief, matching the macOS section's tone. Replace the placeholder with a short paragraph explaining that the PowerShell launcher auto\u2011provisions .NET 10 and warns about missing Git/uv, plus a note that MXC sandboxing is handled separately via `provision-mxc`. Cross\u2011reference TROUBLESHOOTING.md for all details. This minimizes README bloat and works well if the README's install section is meant to stay high\u2011level.\n\n**Option C \u2014 Structured prerequisites table + flow**\nAdd a prerequisites table (Git, .NET 10 SDK, uv, MXC) with one\u2011liner install commands and a \"handled by launcher?\" column. Below it, the clone\u2011and\u2011run flow with a note on what to expect on first launch (the consent prompt for .NET install, the uv warning). Top off with a state\u2011location summary. This is more scannable than prose-heavy Option A while still being self\u2011contained.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"summary\": \"Update the README's Windows installation section, which is currently a placeholder that ignores all Windows-specific prerequisites (Git, .NET 10 SDK, uv), sandboxing (MXC/provision-mxc), state locations, and PowerShell execution-policy caveats. Replace it with accurate, actionable guidance reflecting the real visual-relay.ps1 bootstrap flow and the Windows sandbox setup.\",\n  \"options\": [\n    \"Option A \u2014 Comprehensive step-by-step walkthrough covering prerequisites (Git, .NET 10 SDK, uv) with install commands, clone+launch flow, MXC sandbox setup, state locations, execution-policy tip, and cross-references to TROUBLESHOOTING.md.\",\n    \"Option B \u2014 Concise paragraph explaining what the PowerShell launcher auto-provisions and what remains manual, keeping the section high-level and deferring all detail to TROUBLESHOOTING.md and AGENTS.md.\",\n    \"Option C \u2014 Structured prerequisites table with one-liner install commands and a 'handled by launcher?' column, followed by the clone-and-run flow and a state-location summary, for scannability.\"\n  ]\n}\n```",
